def unique_values(df, exclude_cols=[]):
    for col in df.columns:
        if col in exclude_cols:
            continue
        unique_vals = df[col].nunique()
        print(f"{col}: {unique_vals} unique values")
        if unique_vals < 25:
            print()
            print(df[col].unique())
        print("\n", 55 * "_", "\n")

def check_unknown_values(df):

    for column_name in df.columns:
        unique_values = df[column_name].unique().tolist()
        if 'unknown' in unique_values:
            values = df[column_name].value_counts()
            unknown_counts = values['unknown']
            total_count = len(df)
            unknown_percentage = (unknown_counts/ total_count) * 100
            print(values)
            print(f"\nPercentage of 'unknown' values in {column_name}: {unknown_percentage:.2f}%")
            print("\n", 55 * "_", "\n")

  • As we can see now, in num_con_this_camp - Top 5 - 6 values dominates the distribution...Top 3 values appears in 81% of total no. of instances...

  • Whereas in days_since_last_con - 999 seems to dominate the frequency distribution... Some people, softwares and databases still use and understand 999 or -999 as null value in numerical columns... So, this column seems to be filled with more than 96% of null values. So, it would be inappropriate to impute those many values... So, dropping would be ideal...

  • In num_con_prev_camp - 0 seems to dominate the frequency distribution...86% of customers haven't had any call at all during previous campaign... This might be because the campaign now being conducted on new set of customers for the most part. So, this feature doesn't hold any value at all... So, we would consider dropping this as well...

All three have huge imbalance which is of a scale we can't even think of addressing... Still let's plot these against target variable and take a call...

In [16]:
def plot_discrete_vars(df, discrete_vars, target_var):
    for var in discrete_vars:
        if var != 'age':
            fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(11, 7))
            grouped_data = df.groupby([var, target_var]).size().unstack()
            grouped_data.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, ax=ax)
            ax.set_xlabel(var)
            ax.set_ylabel('Count')
            ax.legend(title=target_var)
            plt.show()

plot_discrete_vars(df, discrete_vars, 'subscribed')

As we can see, these features creates huge imbalance even when plotted against target variable... Also, they visibly are not contributing much to the desirable target which is 'yes'... Let's correlate with target var and confirm...

In [17]:
def calculate_correlation(df, discrete_vars, target_var):
    correlations = []
    for var in discrete_vars:
        if var != 'age':
            crosstab = pd.crosstab(df[var], df[target_var])
            chi2, _, _, _ = chi2_contingency(crosstab)
            n = crosstab.sum().sum()
            phi = np.sqrt(chi2 / n)
            correlations.append((var, phi))

    return correlations

def plot_correlation(correlations):
    df_corr = pd.DataFrame(correlations, columns=['Variable', 'Correlation'])
    df_corr.sort_values(by='Correlation', inplace=True)

    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))
    ax.barh(df_corr['Variable'], df_corr['Correlation'])
    ax.set_xlabel('Correlation')
    ax.set_ylabel('Variable')
    ax.set_title('Correlation between Discrete Variables and Target Variable')
    plt.show()

correlations = calculate_correlation(df, discrete_vars, 'subscribed')
plot_correlation(correlations)

Looks like they don't have much correlation with target variable... So, dropping seems ideal... We could have dropped them straightaway... But we wanted some solid reason to drop them and we have some reasons now to drop them... Hence dropping...

def count_outliers(df):
    outliers = {}
    for col in df.select_dtypes(include='number').columns:
        q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)
        q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)
        iqr = q3 - q1
        upper_bound = q3 + (1.5 * iqr)
        lower_bound = q1 - (1.5 * iqr)
        num_outliers = len(df[(df[col] > upper_bound) | (df[col] < lower_bound)])
        percent_outliers = (num_outliers / len(df)) * 100
        outliers[col] = {'count': num_outliers, 'percent': percent_outliers}
    return outliers

def get_column_ranges(df):
    ranges = {}
    for column in continuous_vars:
        column_min = df[column].min()
        column_max = df[column].max()
        column_range = column_max - column_min
        ranges[column] = [column_min, column_max, column_range]
    return ranges

Checking for range abnormality and scaling the data¶

In [55]:
def get_column_ranges(df):
    ranges = {}
    for column in df.columns:
        column_min = df[column].min()
        column_max = df[column].max()
        column_range = column_max - column_min
        ranges[column] = [column_min, column_max, column_range]
    return ranges

Model Performance Comparison¶

As in this case, we need both false positive as well as false negative to be minimal, we would see F1-score which is combined metric considering both FP and FN...

In [61]:
models = [LogisticRegression(), DecisionTreeClassifier(), RandomForestClassifier(), AdaBoostClassifier(), GradientBoostingClassifier(), KNeighborsClassifier(), SVC(), XGBClassifier()]
model_names = ['LogisticRegression', 'DecisionTreeClassifier', 'RandomForestClassifier', 'AdaBoostClassifier', 'GradientBoostingClassifier', 'KNeighborsClassifier', 'SVC', 'XGBClassifier']

accuracy_train = []
accuracy_val = []
f1_val = []
roc_auc_val = []

for model in models:
    
    mod = model
    mod.fit(X_smote, y_smote)
    y_pred_train = mod.predict(X_smote)
    y_pred_val = mod.predict(X_val_scaled)
    
    accuracy_train.append(accuracy_score(y_smote, y_pred_train))
    accuracy_val.append(accuracy_score(y_val, y_pred_val))
    f1_val.append(f1_score(y_val, y_pred_val))
    roc_auc_val.append(roc_auc_score(y_val, y_pred_val))

data = {'Modelling Algorithm': model_names, 'Train Accuracy': accuracy_train, 'Validation Accuracy': accuracy_val, 'F-1 Score': f1_val, 'ROC AUC': roc_auc_val}

data = pd.DataFrame(data)

data['Difference'] = ((np.abs(data['Train Accuracy'] - data['Validation Accuracy'])) * 100) / (data['Train Accuracy'])

data.sort_values(by='Difference')
